sols_latex:
We begin by calculating the radius of convergence, using the Ratio Test:

\begin{align*}
\lim_{n\to\infty} \left|\frac{(-1)^{n+1}(x+2)^{n+1}}{\sqrt{n+1}}\cdot\frac{\sqrt{n}}{(-1)^n(x+2)^n}\right| &= \lim_{n\to\infty} \sqrt{\frac{n}{n+1}}\cdot |x+2| \\
&= \lim_{n\to\infty} \sqrt{\frac{1}{1+\tfrac{1}{n}}}\cdot |x+2| \\
&= |x+2|
\end{align*}

By the Ratio Test, the series converges if $\displaystyle |x+2| < 1$ and
diverges if $\displaystyle |x+2| > 1$. Now we need to check the
endpoints.

When $\displaystyle x+2 = -1$, that is, $\displaystyle x = -3$, we have

\begin{align*}
\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n(x+2)^n}{\sqrt{n}} &= \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n(-1)^n}{\sqrt{n}} = \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}
\end{align*}

which diverges by the p-series test, since $\displaystyle 1/2 < 1$.

When $\displaystyle x+2 = 1$, that is, $\displaystyle x = -1$, we have

\begin{align*}
\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n(x+2)^n}{\sqrt{n}} &= \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n}{\sqrt{n}} 
\end{align*}

This is an alternating series with

\begin{align*}
b_n &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}
\end{align*}

Clearly, $\displaystyle b_{n+1} \leq b_n$ and
$\displaystyle \lim_{n\to\infty} b_n = 0$. By the Alternating Series
Test,

\begin{align*}
\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n(x+2)^n}{\sqrt{n}} &= \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n}{\sqrt{n}} 
\end{align*}

converges. Therefore, the interval of convergence is
$\displaystyle (-3,-1]$.

sols_raw:
We begin by calculating the radius of convergence, using the Ratio Test:

:&lt;math> 
\displaystyle 
\begin{align}
\lim_{n\to\infty} \left|\frac{(-1)^{n+1}(x+2)^{n+1}}{\sqrt{n+1}}\cdot\frac{\sqrt{n}}{(-1)^n(x+2)^n}\right| &amp; = \lim_{n\to\infty} \sqrt{\frac{n}{n+1}}\cdot |x+2| \\
&amp; = \lim_{n\to\infty} \sqrt{\frac{1}{1+\tfrac{1}{n}}}\cdot |x+2| \\
&amp; = |x+2|
\end{align}
&lt;/math>

By the Ratio Test, the series converges if &lt;math> \displaystyle |x+2| &lt; 1&lt;/math> and diverges if &lt;math> \displaystyle |x+2| > 1&lt;/math>. Now we need to check the endpoints.

When &lt;math> \displaystyle x+2 = -1&lt;/math>, that is, &lt;math> \displaystyle x = -3 &lt;/math>, we have

:&lt;math> 
\displaystyle 
\begin{align}
\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n(x+2)^n}{\sqrt{n}} &amp; = \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n(-1)^n}{\sqrt{n}} = \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}
\end{align}
&lt;/math>

which diverges by the p-series test, since &lt;math> \displaystyle 1/2 &lt; 1 &lt;/math>.

When &lt;math> \displaystyle x+2 = 1&lt;/math>, that is, &lt;math> \displaystyle x = -1 &lt;/math>, we have

:&lt;math> 
\displaystyle 
\begin{align}
\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n(x+2)^n}{\sqrt{n}} &amp; = \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n}{\sqrt{n}} 
\end{align}
&lt;/math>

This is an alternating series with

:&lt;math> 
\displaystyle 
\begin{align}
b_n &amp; = \frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}
\end{align}
&lt;/math>

Clearly, &lt;math> \displaystyle b_{n+1} \leq b_n&lt;/math> and &lt;math> \displaystyle \lim_{n\to\infty} b_n = 0 &lt;/math>. By the Alternating Series Test, 

:&lt;math> 
\displaystyle 
\begin{align}
\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n(x+2)^n}{\sqrt{n}} &amp; = \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n}{\sqrt{n}} 
\end{align}
&lt;/math>

converges. Therefore, the interval of convergence is &lt;math> \displaystyle (-3,-1] &lt;/math>.
